{"title_page": "Seanan McGuire", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n  {{BLP primary sources|date=May 2016}}\n  {{like resume|date=May 2016}}\n}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name = Seanan McGuire\n| image = 20190831RS0179 (48684840236).jpg\n| imagesize = \n| alt = Seanan McGuire\n| caption = McGuire in 2019\n| pseudonym = Mira Grant\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1978|01|05}}\n| birth_place = [[Martinez, California]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| occupation = Writer\n| education = \n| alma_mater = \n| period = \n| genre = [[Urban fantasy]], [[Horror fiction|horror]], [[apocalyptic fiction|apocalyptic]]\n| subject = \n| movement = \n| notableworks = ''Rosemary and Rue'', ''Discount Armageddon'', ''Feed'' (as Mira Grant), the \"Wayward Children\" series\n| spouse = \n| partner = \n| children = \n| relatives = \n| awards = \n| signature = \n| signature_alt = \n| website = {{Official URL}}\n| portaldisp = \n}}\n'''Seanan McGuire''' (pronounced SHAWN-in)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://seananmcguire.com/survey.php|title= Silly Survey Bio|website= SeananMcGuire.com|accessdate=February 19, 2013}}</ref> (born January 5, 1978, in [[Martinez, California]]) is an American author and [[filker]]. In 2010, she was awarded the [[John W. Campbell Award for Best New Writer]] by the 2010 [[World Science Fiction Convention]]. Her novella \"[[Every Heart A Doorway]]\" received the 2016 [[Nebula Award for Best Novella]],<ref name=\"Neb17\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sfwa.org/2017/05/nebula-award-recipients-announced/ |title=Nebula Award Recipients Announced |publisher=[[Science Fiction and Fantasy Writers of America]] |date=2017-05-20 |accessdate=2017-05-21}}</ref> the 2017 [[Hugo Award for Best Novella]],<ref name=\"Hugo17\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/2017-hugo-awards/ |title=2017 Hugo Awards |publisher=World Science Fiction Society |accessdate=2017-08-11 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.thehugoawards.org%2Fhugo-history%2F2017-hugo-awards%2F&date=2017-08-11 |archivedate=2017-08-11 |url-status=live}}</ref> and the 2017 [[Locus Award for Best Novella]].<ref name=\"Loc17\">{{cite web|url=http://www.locusmag.com/News/2017/06/do-not-touch-2017-locus-awards-winners/|title=2017 Locus Awards Winners|date=2017-06-24|website=www.locusmag.com|publisher=Locus Online News|language=en|access-date=2017-06-25}}</ref>\n\nMcGuire, known for her urban fantasy, adopted the [[pseudonym]] '''Mira Grant''' to write science fiction/ horror.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/07/22/631255027/writer-seanan-mcguire-speaks-on-her-many-genres|title=Readers See Themselves In The Many Worlds Of Seanan McGuire|last=Mayer|first=Petra|date=July 22, 2018|website=NPR|access-date=October 26, 2019}}</ref> As Grant she published the political thriller/zombie series Newsflesh, comprising the books ''[[Feed (Grant novel)|Feed]]'' (2010), ''[[Deadline (Grant novel)|Deadline]]'' (2011), ''[[Blackout (Grant novel)|Blackout]]'' (2012), nominated for a 2013 [[Hugo Award]] for Best Novel, and ''Feedback'' (2016). Additionally, in 2017, ''The Wine in Dreams'' was published as part of the novella collection [[Star Wars: From a Certain Point of View|Star Wars: Canto Bight]], a tie-in to the 2017 film [[Star Wars: The Last Jedi]].\n\nIn 2013, McGuire received a record five Hugo nominations in total, two for works as Grant and the other three under her own name.<ref name=Grdn />\n\n== Biography ==\nMcGuire was born in California.  . She has an affinity for venomous reptiles and adventure. She has described her interests as including \"swamps, long walks, long walks ''in'' swamps, things that live in swamps, horror movies, strange noises, musical theater, reality TV, comic books, finding pennies on the street, and venomous reptiles.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://seananmcguire.com/bio.php|title=Seanan McGuire: Biography|website=seananmcguire.com|access-date=2018-03-28}}</ref>  She identifies as pansexual,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://justlovereviews.com/2017/09/07/women-in-queer-sff-seanan-mcguire/|title=Women in Queer SFF: Interview with Seanan McGuire|date=Sep 7, 2017|accessdate=Sep 26, 2019}}</ref> or bisexual,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/seananmcguire/status/590979380660178944|title=I am not a lesbian when I am with a woman. I am not straight when I am with a man. I am not asexual when I am with neither. I'm bi.|first=Seanan|last=McGuire|date=Apr 22, 2015|accessdate=Sep 26, 2019}}</ref> and demisexual.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/seananmcguire/status/831207171643695104|title=My name is pronounced SHAWN-in, and while there are many aspects to the book that are not mine, I identify as demisexual.|first=Seanan|last=McGuire|date=Feb 13, 2017|accessdate=Nov 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Novels ==\n\n=== October Daye ===\n# ''Rosemary and Rue'' (September 1, 2009, {{ISBN|978-0-7564-0571-7}})\n# ''A Local Habitation'' (March 2, 2010, {{ISBN|978-0-7564-0596-0}})\n# ''An Artificial Night'' (September 7, 2010, {{ISBN|978-0-7564-0626-4}})\n# ''Late Eclipses'' (March 1, 2011, {{ISBN|978-0-7564-0666-0}})\n# ''One Salt Sea'' (September 6, 2011, {{ISBN|978-0-7564-0683-7}})\n# ''Ashes of Honor'' (September 4, 2012, {{ISBN|978-0-7564-0749-0}})\n# ''Chimes at Midnight'' (September 3, 2013, {{ISBN|978-0-7564-0814-5}})\n# ''The Winter Long '' (September 2, 2014, {{ISBN|978-0-7564-0808-4}})\n# ''A Red Rose Chain'' (September 1, 2015, {{ISBN|978-0756408091}})<ref name=\"Toby Daye bibliography\">{{cite web|last1=McGuire|first1=Seanan|title=The October Daye Books|url=http://seananmcguire.com/toby.php|website=www.seananmcguire.com|accessdate=11 January 2015}}</ref>\n# ''Once Broken Faith'' (September 6, 2016, {{ISBN|978-1472151056}})\n# ''The Brightest Fell'' (September 5, 2017, {{ISBN|978-0756413316}})<ref name=\"Toby Daye bibliography\" />\n# ''Night and Silence'' (September 4, 2018, {{ISBN|9780756414764}})<ref name=\"Toby Daye bibliography\" />\n# ''The Unkindest Tide'' (September 3, 2019, DAW {{ISBN|9780756415075}})<<ref>https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/series/BK8/october-daye</ref>>\n# ''A Killing Frost'' (expected September 1, 2020, DAW {{ISBN|9780756415082}})<<ref>https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/series/BK8/october-daye</ref>>\n\n=== InCryptid ===\n# ''Discount Armageddon'' (March 6, 2012, {{ISBN|978-0-7564-0713-1}})\n# ''Midnight Blue-Light Special'' (March 5, 2013, {{ISBN|978-0-7564-0792-6}})\n# ''Half-Off Ragnarok'' (March 4, 2014, {{ISBN|978-0-7564-0811-4}})\n# ''Pocket Apocalypse'' (March 3, 2015, {{ISBN|978-0-7564-0812-1}})\n# ''Chaos Choreography'' (March 1, 2016, {{ISBN|978-0-7564-0813-8}})\n# ''Magic for Nothing'' (March 7, 2017, {{ISBN|978-0-7564-1039-1}})\n# ''Tricks for Free'' (March 6, 2018, {{ISBN|978-0-7564-1040-7}})<ref name=\"family reunion\">{{cite web|last1=McGuire|first1=Seanan|title=Guess Who's Coming to the Family Reunion?|url=http://seanan-mcguire.livejournal.com/563851.html|accessdate=11 January 2015}}</ref>\n#''That Ain't Witchcraft'' (March 5, 2019, {{ISBN|978-0756411794}})\n#''Imaginary Numbers'' (February 25, 2020, DAW {{ISBN|9780756413781}})<ref>https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/series/BBS/incryptid/</ref>\n#''Calculated Risks'' (Expected February or March, 2021, DAW)<ref>{{cite book |last1=McGuire |first1=Seanan |title=Imaginary Numbers |date=February 25, 2020 |publisher=DAW |isbn=9780756413781 |page=435}}</ref>\n\n=== Newsflesh (as Mira Grant) ===\n\n*{{cite book|title=''Newsflesh 1.0:'' Feed|date=April 27, 2010|isbn= 978-0-316-08105-4|publisher=Orbit|title-link=Feed (Grant novel)}} (Novel)\n**{{cite book|title=''Newsflesh 1.5:'' Fed|date=May 16, 2012|url=http://www.orbitbooks.net/2012/05/23/what-if-things-had-ended-differently-fed-by-mira-grant/|publisher=Orbit}} (A free digital novella presenting an alternate ending to ''Feed'')\n*{{cite book|title=''Newsflesh 2.0:'' Deadline|date=May 31, 2011|isbn= 978-0-316-08106-1|publisher=Orbit|title-link=Deadline (Grant novel)}}\n*{{cite book|title=''Newsflesh