r = Orbit Books|accessdate = Nov 3, 2013|date = 2013-10-29}}</ref>\n# ''Symbiont'' (November 25, 2014, {{ISBN|978-0-316-21899-3}})\n# ''Chimera'' (November 24, 2015, {{ISBN|978-0-316-38103-1}}) <ref>{{cite book|title=Chimera (Parasitology): Mira Grant: 9780316381031: Amazon.com: Books |date= 2015-11-24|isbn = 978-0316381031|last1 = Grant|first1 = Mira}}</ref>\n\n=== Velveteen ===\n# ''Velveteen vs. the Junior Super Patriots'' (November 9, 2012, {{ISBN|978-0-98579-891-8}}, [[ISFiC Press]])\n# ''Velveteen vs. the Multiverse'' (August 23, 2013, {{ISBN|978-0-98579-896-3}}, ISFiC Press)\n# ''Velveteen vs. the Seasons'' (May 6, 2016, {{ISBN|978-0-99100-267-2}}, ISFiC Press)\n\n=== Indexing ===\n# ''Indexing'' (January 24, 2014, {{ISBN|978-1-4778-0960-0}})\n# ''Indexing: Reflections'' (2015, {{ISBN|978-1-5039-4774-0}})<ref>{{cite web|last1=McGuire|first1=Seanan|title=Everyone knew how the story would go: crows on the battlements, blood on the snow.|url=http://seanan-mcguire.livejournal.com/584824.html|accessdate=11 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Wayward Children ===\n# ''[[Every Heart a Doorway]]'' (April 5, 2016, {{ISBN|978-0-76538-5-505}})\n# ''Down Among the Sticks and Bones'' (June 13, 2017, {{ISBN|978-0-76539-2-039}})\n# ''Beneath the Sugar Sky'' (January 9, 2018, {{ISBN|978-0-765393-586}})\n# ''In an Absent Dream'' (January 8, 2019, {{ISBN|978-0-765399-298}})\n# ''Come Tumbling Down'' (January 7, 2020, {{ISBN|9780765399311}})\n\n=== Ghost Stories ===\n# ''Sparrow Hill Road'' (May 6, 2014, {{ISBN|978-0-7564-0961-6}})\n# ''The Girl in the Green Silk Gown'' (July 17, 2018, {{ISBN|978-0-7564-1380-4}})\n\n=== Drowning Deep (as Mira Grant) ===\n# {{cite book|title=Rolling in the Deep|url=https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00VR2L60S/ref=dbs_a_def_rwt_hsch_vapi_tkin_p1_i2|asin=B00VR2L60S|date=April 6, 2015|publisher=Subterranean Press }}\n# ''[[Into the Drowning Deep]]''. Orbit. November 14, 2017. [https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B06Y5L7H71/ref=dbs_a_def_rwt_hsch_vapi_tkin_p1_i0 ASIN  B06Y5L7H71]\n\n=== Alien ===\n* ''Alien: Echo''. Imprint. (April 9, 2019, {{ISBN|9781250306296}}.)\n\n=== Middlegame ===\n# ''Middlegame'' (May 7, 2019, {{ISBN|9781250195524}})\n\n== Non-fiction ==\n* \"Mathematical Excellence\" in ''Chicks Dig Time Lords'' (March 2010)\n* \"Introduction\" in ''In A Gilded Light'' (Jennifer Brozek, September 2010)\n* \"The Girls Next Door: Learning to Live With the Living Dead and Never Even Break a Nail\" in ''Whedonistas'' (March 2011)\n* \"Summers and Winters, Frost and Flame\" in ''Chicks Dig Comics'' (April 2012)\n* ''Letters to the Pumpkin King'' (February 2014, {{ISBN|978-1-61037-304-3}})\n\n== Albums ==\n\n* ''Pretty Little Dead Girl: Seanan McGuire and Friends Live at OVFF 2005'' (2006)\n* ''Stars Fall Home'' (2007)\n* ''Red Roses and Dead Things'' (2009)\n* ''Wicked Girls'' (2011)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://seananmcguire.com/musicfaq.php |title=Music and Filk FAQ |publisher=Seanan McGuire |access-date=2018-03-28 }}</ref>\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\nMcGuire was awarded the [[John W. Campbell Award for Best New Writer]] by the 2010 [[World Science Fiction Convention]].<ref name=\"Hugo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/campbell-history/ |title=John W. Campbell Award History|website=http://www.thehugoawards.org/campbell-history/}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, McGuire's novel ''Feed'' (written under the [[pseudonym]] Mira Grant) ranked #74 in a [[National Public Radio]] listener poll of the top 100 [[thriller (genre)|thriller]] novels of all time.<ref name=\"Audience Picks: Top 100 'Killer Thrillers'\">{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=128718927 |title=Audience Picks: Top 100 'Killer Thrillers'|work=NPR|date=2010}}</ref>  ''Feed'' was also selected by [[Publishers Weekly]] as one of their Best Books of 2010.<ref name=\"Publishers Weekly Best Books of 2010\">{{cite web|url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/book-news/awards-and-prizes/article/45070-best-books-of-2010.html?page=3|title=Publishers Weekly Best Books of 2010|publisher=|accessdate=28 October 2018}}</ref> It was nominated for the 2011 Shirley Jackson Award, as well as the 2011 [[Hugo Award for Best Novel]].<ref name=\"Hugo11\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.renovationsf.org/cgi-sys/suspendedpage.cgi|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110429050214/http://www.renovationsf.org/hugo-intro.php|url-status=dead|title=Account Suspended|archivedate=April 29, 2011|website=www.renovationsf.org|accessdate=Sep 26, 2019}}</ref> Its sequel, ''Deadline'', was also nominated for the 2012 Hugo Award for Best Novel. The stand-alone Newsflesh story ''Countdown'' was nominated for the 2012 Best Novella Hugo. Her [[filk]] album ''Wicked Girls'' was nominated for the 2012 Best Related Work Hugo. The ''[[SF Squeecast]]'', a podcast to which she contributes, won the 2012 [[Hugo Award]] for best fancast.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/2012-hugo-awards/ | title=2012 Hugo Awards | publisher=The Hugo Awards | accessdate=April 9, 2012 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/66nnsGGRI?url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/2012-hugo-awards/ | archivedate=April 9, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nMcGuire was the inductee into the 2012 [[Darrell Awards]] Hall of Fame for her contributions to mid-south science fiction.<ref name=\"Darrell Awards\">{{cite web|url=http://freepages.misc.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~timgatewood/sf/darrell/|title=The Darrell Awards|publisher=|accessdate=28 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160411200829/http://freepages.misc.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~timgatewood/sf/darrell/|archive-date=11 April 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n''SF Squeecast'' won its second Hugo in 2013. ''Blackout'' received a 2013 Hugo nomination for Best Novel. In addition, McGuire received three other nominations (a record five nominations in a single year): best novella (as Grant) and twice for best novelette (both as McGuire).<ref name=Grdn>{{cite news|last=Flood|first=Alison|title=Seanan McGuire gets record five nominations for Hugo awards|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/mar/31/seanan-mcguire-hugo-awards-shortlist|accessdate=31 March 2013|newspaper=The Guardian|date=31 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nMcGuire won the 2016 [[Nebula Award]] for Best Novella for ''Every Heart a Doorway''.<ref name=\"Neb17\" />  McGuire has won six [[Pegasus Award]]s:<ref name=\"pegasus\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ovff.org/pegasus/people/seanan-mcguire.html|title=Pegasus Awards \u2013 Seanan McGuire|website=www.ovff.org|accessdate=28 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n''Every Heart a Doorway'' was nominated for a [[World Fantasy Award\u2014Long Fiction|World Fantasy Award]] in 2017. ''Beneath the Sugar Sky'' was nominated for the 2019 [[World Fantasy Award for Best Novella]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldfantasy.org/world-fantasy-awards%e2%84%a0-2019/|title=World Fantasy Awards\u2120 2019 {{!}} World Fantasy Convention|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref>\n\nMcGuire has won the [[American Library Association]]'s [[Alex Award]] twice: in 2017 for ''Every Heart a Doorway'' <ref name=\"alex17\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ala.org/yalsa/2017-alex-awards|title=Alex Awards 2017 |website=www.ala.org|accessdate=21 November 2018|date=2018-02-13 }}</ref> and in 2018 for ''Down Among the Sticks and Bones''.<ref name=\"alex18\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ala.org/news/press-releases/2018/02/yalsa-announces-2018-alex-awards|title=Alex Awards 2018|website=www.ala.org|accessdate=21 November 2018|date=2018-02-12}}</ref> This makes her the first author to win the award in two consecutive years.<ref name=\"alextor\">{{cite web|url=https://www.tor.com/2018/02/12/seanan-mcguires-down-among-the-sticks-and-bones-martha-wells-all-systems-red-2018-alex-award-winners-ala/|title=Alex Awards Tor Press Release|website=www.tor.com|accessdate=21 November 2018|date=2018-02-12}}</ref>\n\nMcGuire has received three nominations for the [[Hugo Award for Best Series]]. The October Daye series was nominated in 2017 and 2019, and the InCryptid series was nominated in 2018.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Organization\n!Award\n!Category\n!Work\n!Result\n!Source\n|-\n|2019\n|[[World Science Fiction Convention]]\n|[[Hugo Award|Hugo]]\n|Best Series\n|October Daye\n|{{nom}}\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|[[World Science Fiction Convention]]\n|[[Hugo Award|Hugo]]\n|Best Novella\n|Beneath the Sugar Sky\n|{{Nominated}}\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|[[World Science Fiction Convention]]\n|[[Hugo Award|Hugo]]\n|Best Novella\n|Down Among the Sticks and Bones\n|{{Nominated}}\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|[[World Science Fiction Convention]]\n|[[Hugo Award|Hugo]]\n|Best Series\n|InCryptid\n|{{Nominated}}\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|[[World Science Fiction Convention]]\n|[[Hugo Award|Hugo]]\n|[[Hugo Award for Best Novella|Best Novella]]\n|Every Heart a Doorway\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|[[World Science Fiction Convention]]\n|[[Hugo Award|Hugo]]\n|Best Series\n|October Daye\n|{{nom}}\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|[[Science Fiction and Fantasy Writers of America|Science Fiction Writers of America]]\n|[[Nebula Award|Nebula]]\n|[[Nebula Award for Best Novella|Best Novella]]\n|Every Heart a Doorway\n|{{won}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nebulas.sfwa.org/award/best-novella/|title=Nebula Awards Nominees and Winners: Best Novella Nebula Awards|website=The Nebula Awards|access-date=2019-04-03}}</ref>\n|-\n|2013\n|[[World Science Fiction Convention]]\n|[[Hugo Award|Hugo]]\n|[[Hugo Award for Best Novel|Best Novel]]\n|Blackout (as Mira Grant)\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/2013-hugo-awards/|title=2013 Hugo Awards|date=2012-12-22|website=The Hugo Awards|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-03}}</ref>\n|-\n|2013\n|[[World Science Fiction Convention]]\n|[[Hugo Award|Hugo]]\n|[[Hugo Award for Best Novelette|Best Novelette]]\n|In Sea-Salt Tears\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":0\" />\n|-\n|2013\n|[[World Science Fiction Convention]]\n|[[Hugo Award|Hugo]]\n|[[Hugo Award fo